{"questionId":"9070940","questionHtml":"<p>Which terms describe the nitronium ion in the nitration of benzene?</p>\n<p style=\"text-align:center;\"><img src=\"__IMG__/7c8e8e9260afa3a22ce6362d18a67a5c05299c13.png\"></p>\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n<table style=\"height:151px;width:357px;\" border=\"1\" cellspacing=\"0\" cellpadding=\"2\">\n<tbody>\n<tr>\n<td style=\"width:37.4884px;\">&nbsp;</td>\n<td style=\"text-align:center;width:142.072px;\"><strong>Type of reactant</strong></td>\n<td style=\"text-align:center;width:159.56px;\"><strong>Acid-base nature</strong></td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td style=\"width:37.4884px;\">A.&nbsp;&nbsp;</td>\n<td style=\"text-align:center;width:142.072px;\">nucleophile</td>\n<td style=\"text-align:center;width:159.56px;\">Lewis base</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td style=\"width:37.4884px;\">B.&nbsp;&nbsp;</td>\n<td style=\"text-align:center;width:142.072px;\">nucleophile</td>\n<td style=\"text-align:center;width:159.56px;\">Lewis acid</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td style=\"width:37.4884px;\">C.&nbsp;&nbsp;</td>\n<td style=\"text-align:center;width:142.072px;\">electrophile</td>\n<td style=\"text-align:center;width:159.56px;\">Lewis base</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td style=\"width:37.4884px;\">D.&nbsp;&nbsp;</td>\n<td style=\"text-align:center;width:142.072px;\">electrophile</td>\n<td style=\"text-align:center;width:159.56px;\">Lewis acid</td>\n</tr>\n</tbody>\n</table>","markschemeHtml":"<p>D</p>","meta":{"questionId":"9070940","referenceCode":"23M.1.HL.TZ1.37","subjectId":"45-dp-chemistry-last-assessment-2024","title":"Which terms describe the nitronium ion in the nitration of benzene? Type of reactant Acid-base nature A. nucleophile Lewis base B. nucleophile Lewis acid C. electrophile Lewis base","paper":"1","level":"HL","questionNumber":"37","marksAvailable":"[Maximum mark: 1]","breadcrumbLabels":["Additional higher level (AHL)","Additional higher level (AHL)","Topic 14: Chemical bonding and structure","14.1 Covalent bonding and electron domain and molecular geometries","Ad